\begin_layout Standard
In the previous sections, we have seen that even with a smooth IC, the smooth
 solution of a quasilinear PDE (system) can finally become discontinuous.
 To handle such cases, we have to extend the notion of solutions to a weaker
 sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
守恒律
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a 
\noun on
control volume
\noun default
 (CV)
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CV"
description "Control Volume"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
control!~ volume
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V$
\end_inset

 is the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, known as a 
\noun on
control surface
\noun default
 (CS)
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CS"
description "Control Surface"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
control!~ surface
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{c}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\vec{u}^{c}$"
description "velocity of a point on a control surface"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 is the velocity of a point on 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $^{c}$
\end_inset

 stands for 
\bar under
c
\bar default
ontrol volume)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the 
\noun on
conservation variable
\noun default
, usually the 
\noun on
density
\noun default
 of some physical quantity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\noun on
flux vector
\noun default
, i.e.
 how much such quantity passes through a 
\emph on
fixed
\emph default
 surface in space per unit area within unit time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, the 
\noun on
conservation law
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
conservation!~ law!~ in integral form
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{V}\pdv{\phi}{t}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vec{n}\cdot\vec{f}\dd{S}=0\label{ConservationLawIntegralForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or equivalently
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dv{t}\int_{V}\phi\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vec{n}\cdot\left(\vec{f}-\phi\vec{u}^{c}\right)\dd{S}=0\label{eq:ConservationLawOnMovingControlVolume}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is usually used for 
\emph on
moving
\emph default
 control volumes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 smooth with respect to spatial variables, we can apply Gauss's divergence
 theorem to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "ConservationLawIntegralForm"

\end_inset

, which leads to
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
conservation!~ law!~ in differential form
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{\phi}{t}+\grad\cdot\vec{f}=0
\]

\end_inset

If the smoothness requirement is not satisfied, we should go back to the
 integral form, which will leads to the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "subsec:JumpConditions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation
For a vector conservation law, or a system of conservation laws, we use
 a column matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

 for the conservation variables, a scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}:=\ip{i}{U}$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation
In 3D space, we use a column matrix of vectors (or tensors) 
\begin_inset Formula $\VecInKet{F}$
\end_inset

 for the flux, which can be decomposed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\VecInKet{F}=\sum_{k=1}^{3}\vec{e}_{k}\ket{F_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 The conservation law is then written in one of the following forms
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dv{t}\int_{V}\ket{U}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vec{n}\cdot\left(\VecInKet{F}-\vec{u}^{c}\ket{U}\right)\dd{S}=\ket{0}\label{eq:ConservationLawSystemOnMovingControlVolume}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{V}\pdv{\ket{U}}{t}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vec{n}\cdot\VecInKet{F}\dd{S}=\ket{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pdv{\ket{U}}{t}+\grad\cdot{\VecInKet{F}}=\ket{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In Cartesian coordinates, the last one is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\pdv{\ket{U}}{t}+\sum_{k=1}^{3}\pdv{\ket{F_{k}}}{x_{k}}=\ket{0}}\label{eq:ConservationLaws3dSystem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation
In 1D space, only one component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\VecInKet{F}$
\end_inset

 is non-zero, so the subscripts can be ignored.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationLaws3dSystem"

\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\pdv{\ket{U}}{t}+\pdv{\ket{F}}{x}=\ket{0}}\label{eq:ConservationLaws1dSystem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation
Scalar conservation laws are just special cases of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationLaws3dSystem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationLaws1dSystem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phantom{U}}$
\end_inset

 can be ignored, that is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\pdv{U}{t}+\sum_{k=1}^{3}\pdv{F_{k}}{x_{k}}=0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 3D problems, and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\pdv{U}{t}+\pdv{F}{x}=0}\label{eq:ConservationLaw1dScalar}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 1D problems.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
跳跃关系
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:JumpConditions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose there is a discontinuity manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 moving with velocity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{u}^{s}=\vec{e}_{\perp}u_{\perp}^{s}+\vec{e}_{\parallel}u_{\parallel}^{s}
\]

\end_inset

Choose a cylindrical control volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 satisfying the following requirements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It has an infinitesimal height 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, which means
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{h\to0}\vec{u}^{c}=\vec{u}^{s}\qquad\lim_{h\to0}\int_{V}\ket{U}\dd{V}=\ket{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
All of its walls are 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is sandwiched between the top surface 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{+}$
\end_inset

 (on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}=\vec{e}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

) and the bottom surface 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{-}$
\end_inset

 (on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}=-\vec{e}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{+}\parallel S\parallel S_{-}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, the conservation law on a moving control volume 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationLawSystemOnMovingControlVolume"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is reduced to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{S_{+}\cup S_{-}}\vec{n}\cdot\left(\VecInKet{F}-\vec{u}^{s}\ket{U}\right)\dd{S}=0
\]

\end_inset

Replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm\vec{e}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{S_{\pm}}\dd{S}\to0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\vec{e}_{\perp}\cdot\vec{u}^{s}\right)\left(\ket{U_{+}}-\ket{U_{-}}\right)=\vec{e}_{\perp}\cdot\ket*{\vec{F}_{+}}-\vec{e}_{\perp}\cdot\ket*{\vec{F}_{-}}
\]

\end_inset

or written in a more compact form
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:JumpConditions"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\eval{\ket{U}}_{-}^{+}u_{\perp}^{s}=\eval{\ket{F_{\perp}}}_{-}^{+}}\qquad u_{\perp}^{s}:=\vec{e}_{\perp}\cdot\vec{u}^{s}\qquad\ket{F_{\perp}}:=\vec{e}_{\perp}\cdot\VecInKet{F}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is known as the 
\noun on
Rankine–Hugoniot condition
\noun default
, a.k.a.
 the 
\noun on
jump condition
\noun default
.
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
condition!jump ~!RankineHugoniot@Rankine–Hugoniot's ~
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1D space, only one component of a vector is non-zero, for which the subscript
 can be ignored:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{e}_{\perp}=\vec{e}_{1}\qquad\vec{u}^{s}=\vec{e}_{1}u^{s}\qquad\VecInKet{F}=\vec{e}_{1}\ket{F}
\]

\end_inset

The jump condition can then be simplified as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eval{\ket{U}}_{-}^{+}u^{s}=\eval{\ket{F}}_{-}^{+}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for a system of conservation laws, and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eval{U}_{-}^{+}u^{s}=\eval{F}_{-}^{+}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for a single conservation law.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
弱解
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[Weak Solution of Single Conservation Law]
\end_layout

\end_inset

If there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 integrable function 
\begin_inset Formula $U(x,t)$
\end_inset

 that satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned} & \int_{t_{0}}^{+\infty}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\left(\pdv{\phi}{t}U+\pdv{\phi}{x}F\right)\dd{x}\dd{t}\\
+ & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\phi(x_{0},t_{0})U_{0}(x_{0})\dd{x_{0}}\\
= & 0
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

for any 
\emph on
compact supported smooth
\emph default
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x,t)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $U(x,t)$
\end_inset

 is said to be a 
\noun on
weak solution
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
solution!weak ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationLaw1dScalar"

\end_inset

 (a scalar conservation law in 1D space) with the 
\emph on
piecewise smooth
\emph default
 IC
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(x_{0},t_{0})=U_{0}(x_{0})\qquad x_{0}\in(-\infty,\infty)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Any smooth solution is also a weak solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For smooth solutions, we can move the temporal derivative from 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned} & \int_{t_{0}}^{+\infty}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\pdv{\phi}{t}U\dd{x}\dd{t}\\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{t_{0}}^{+\infty}\left(-\phi\pdv{U}{t}+\pdv{\phi U}{t}\right)\dd{t}\dd{x}\\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{t_{0}}^{+\infty}-\phi\pdv{U}{t}\dd{t}\dd{x}+\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\eval{\phi U}_{t_{0}}^{+\infty}\dd{x}\\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{t_{0}}^{+\infty}-\phi\pdv{U}{t}\dd{t}\dd{x}-\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\phi(x_{0},t_{0})U_{0}(x_{0})\dd{x_{0}}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

We drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $t=+\infty$
\end_inset

 term since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t=+\infty,x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Similarly, we can move the spatial derivative from 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned} & \int_{t_{0}}^{+\infty}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\pdv{\phi}{x}F\dd{x}\dd{t}\\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{t_{0}}^{+\infty}\left(-\phi\pdv{F}{x}+\pdv{\phi F}{x}\right)\dd{t}\dd{x}\\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{t_{0}}^{+\infty}-\phi\pdv{F}{x}\dd{t}\dd{x}+\int_{t_{0}}^{+\infty}\eval{\phi F}_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\dd{t}\\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{t_{0}}^{+\infty}-\phi\pdv{F}{x}\dd{t}\dd{x}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

We drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\pm\infty$
\end_inset

 terms since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t,x=\pm\infty)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Substitute them back into the definition of weak solution, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\int_{t_{0}}^{+\infty}-\phi\left(\pdv{U}{t}+\pdv{F}{x}\right)\dd{t}\dd{x}=0
\]

\end_inset

which leads to the PDE since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is chosen arbitrarily.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For conservation law systems, just replace 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{F}$
\end_inset

.
 For 3D problems, just replace 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pdv*{x}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\grad$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
熵条件
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mathematically, there might be more than one weak solutions.
 However, for a problem with physical backgrounds, there is only one solution,
 which satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the PDE in smooth regions,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
jump conditions across discontinuities,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
entropy conditions across discontinuities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a single conservation law in 1D space, the entropy condition is given
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Lax"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Lax"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
condition!entropy ~!Lax's ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a(U_{-})\ge u^{s}\ge a(U_{+})
\]

\end_inset

which has a clear geometric interpretation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact
Characteristic curves near the discontinuity curve must run into or at least
 be parallel with it as 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a system of conservation law, the entropy condition
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
condition!entropy ~!Lax's ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is given as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{gathered}\lambda_{k}(U_{-})\ge u^{s}\ge\lambda_{k}(U_{+})\\
\lambda_{k-1}(U_{-})<u^{s}<\lambda_{k+1}(U_{+})
\end{gathered}
\label{eq:EntropyConditionForSystem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some index 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the terminology of gas dynamics, we can classify various discontinuities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the entropy condition takes an equal sign, it implies a 
\noun on
contact discontinuity
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
discontinuity!contact ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which means there is no mass/momentum/energy flowing through the discontinuity
 surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the entropy condition takes a strict unequal sign, it implies a 
\noun on
shock wave
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
discontinuity!shock wave
\end_layout

\end_inset

, across which entropy is strictly increased.
\end_layout

