The following univariate function for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}\ge0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(p_{2};p_{1},\rho_{1})=\begin{cases}
(p_{2}-p_{1})/\sqrt{\rho_{1}P} & p_{2}>p_{1}\\
0 & p_{2}=p_{1}\\
\frac{2a_{1}}{\gamma-1}\left[\left(p_{2}/p_{1}\right)^{\frac{\gamma-1}{2\gamma}}-1\right] & p_{2}<p_{1}
\end{cases}\label{eq:PressureFunctionForSingleWave}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is continuously differentiable and monotonically increasing for any fixed
 positive values of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\frac{\gamma+1}{2}p_{2}+\frac{\gamma-1}{2}p_{1}\qquad a_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{\gamma p_{1}}{\rho_{1}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Denote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{1}(p_{2})=\frac{p_{2}-p_{1}}{\sqrt{\rho_{1}P}}\qquad f_{2}(p_{2})=\frac{2a_{1}}{\gamma-1}\left[\left(p_{2}/p_{1}\right)^{\frac{\gamma-1}{2\gamma}}-1\right]
\]

\end_inset

It is obvious that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}(p_{1})=0=f_{2}(p_{1})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The differentiability of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 comes from the fact that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{-}}f_{1}'(p_{1}+\epsilon)=\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}f_{2}'(p_{1}+\epsilon)
\]

\end_inset

which is justified from
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}\dv{f_{1}}{p_{2}} & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{\rho_{1}P}}+\frac{p_{2}-p_{1}}{\sqrt{\rho_{1}}}\dv{P^{-1/2}}{p_{2}}\\
 & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{\rho_{1}P}}+\frac{p_{2}-p_{1}}{\sqrt{\rho_{1}}}\left(-\frac{1}{2}P^{-3/2}\right)\dv{P}{p_{2}}\\
 & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{\rho_{1}P}}\left(1-\frac{\gamma+1}{4}\frac{p_{2}-p_{1}}{P}\right)\\
\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{-}}f_{1}'(p_{1}+\epsilon) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{\rho_{1}\gamma p_{1}}}
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset

and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}\dv{f_{2}}{p_{2}} & =\frac{2a_{1}}{\gamma-1}\frac{\gamma-1}{2\gamma}\left(\frac{p_{2}}{p_{1}}\right)^{\frac{\gamma-1}{2\gamma}-1}\frac{1}{p_{1}}\\
 & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{\rho_{1}\gamma p_{1}}}\left(\frac{p_{2}}{p_{1}}\right)^{-\frac{\gamma+1}{2\gamma}}\\
\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}f_{2}'(p_{1}+\epsilon) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{\rho_{1}\gamma p_{1}}}
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The monotonicity of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(p_{2})>0$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}>0$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f'(p_{2})=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{\rho_{1}P}}\left(1-\frac{\gamma+1}{4}\frac{p_{2}-p_{1}}{P}\right) & p_{2}>p_{1}\\
\frac{1}{\sqrt{\rho_{1}\gamma p_{1}}} & p_{2}=p_{1}\\
\frac{1}{\sqrt{\rho_{1}\gamma p_{1}}}\left(p_{2}/p_{1}\right)^{-\frac{\gamma+1}{2\gamma}} & p_{2}<p_{1}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

The 2nd and 3rd cases are trivial, while the 1st one is positive since when
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}>p_{1}$
\end_inset

, there is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-\frac{\gamma+1}{4}\frac{p_{2}-p_{1}}{P}=1-\frac{1}{2}\frac{p_{2}-p_{1}}{p_{2}+\frac{\gamma-1}{\gamma+1}p_{1}}>1-\frac{1}{2}>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
The following univariate function for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}\ge0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F(p_{2};p_{\pm},\rho_{\pm})=f(p_{2};p_{-},\rho_{-})+f(p_{2};p_{+},\rho_{+})\label{eq:PressureFunctionForDoubleWave}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is continuously differentiable and monotonically increasing for any fixed
 positive values of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\pm},\rho_{\pm}$
\end_inset

, and there is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{p_{2}\to0^{+}}F(p_{2};p_{\pm},\rho_{\pm})=-\frac{2a_{-}}{\gamma-1}-\frac{2a_{+}}{\gamma-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
接触间断两侧的状态
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall the solution structure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RiemannSolutionStructureForEuler1d"

\end_inset

 discussed above, we've already known that the 2nd elementary wave 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 is always a contact, across which the two generalized Riemann invariants,
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, are constant, which we shall denote as 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Such constancy holds in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{3}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

 are constant across 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}\cup E_{2}\cup C_{3}$
\end_inset

, which are the right values of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the left values for 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a left running shock if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}>p_{-}$
\end_inset

, or a rarefaction if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}<p_{-}$
\end_inset

.
 In either case, there is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{2}-u_{-}=-f(p_{2};p_{-},\rho_{-})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PressureFunctionForSingleWave"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Formula $E_{3}$
\end_inset

 is a right running shock if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}>p_{+}$
\end_inset

, or a rarefaction if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}<p_{+}$
\end_inset

.
 In either case, there is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{2}-u_{+}=+f(p_{2};p_{+},\rho_{+})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PressureFunctionForSingleWave"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
For any fixed positive values of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\pm},\rho_{\pm}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{-}-u_{+}>F(0;p_{\pm},\rho_{\pm})$
\end_inset

 or equivalently
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{-}+\frac{2a_{-}}{\gamma-1}>u_{+}-\frac{2a_{+}}{\gamma-1}
\]

\end_inset

then the following equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}>0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{-}-u_{+}=F(p_{2};p_{\pm},\rho_{\pm})\label{eq:EquationForP2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

will have a unique solution, in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{2}=\frac{1}{2}\left[u_{-}+u_{+}+f(p_{2};p_{+},\rho_{+})-f(p_{2};p_{-},\rho_{-})\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{-}-u_{+}\le F(0;p_{\pm},\rho_{\pm})$
\end_inset

 or equivalently
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{-}+\frac{2a_{-}}{\gamma-1}\le u_{+}-\frac{2a_{+}}{\gamma-1}\label{eq:VacuumCondition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

then Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EquationForP2"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}>0$
\end_inset

 will have no solution, which indicates something is wrong in the derivation
 of Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EquationForP2"

\end_inset

.
 Physically, pressure is a measure of the intensity of gas molecules' thermal
 motion, so 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 can only appears in a region of vacuum.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:VacuumCondition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is then called the 
\noun on
vacuum condition
\noun default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
condition!vacuum ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which means if the initial velocity gap 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{-}-u_{+})$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently large, the flow field will be torn into two independent
 regions, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\cup E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{3}\cup C_{4}$
\end_inset

, being connected by a vacuumed region, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}\cup E_{2}\cup C_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 It is reasonable to set 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}=0$
\end_inset

) inside the vacuumed region.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 does not have to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\pm}>p_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{3}$
\end_inset

 will both be rarefactions, inside which, states can be determined from
 the two Riemann invariants.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

, they are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{1}=\frac{p}{\rho^{\gamma}}=\frac{p_{-}}{\rho_{-}^{\gamma}}\qquad\phi_{2}=u+\frac{2a}{\gamma-1}=u_{-}+\frac{2a_{-}}{\gamma-1}
\]

\end_inset

The speed of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

's head is simply
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
